Here’s an updated version that adds basic error handling by validating inputs and guarding against division by zero. It throws descriptive errors so callers can handle them with try/catch.

Code:
function divide(a, b) {
  // Ensure both inputs are numbers
  if (typeof a !== 'number' || typeof b !== 'number' || Number.isNaN(a) || Number.isNaN(b)) {
    throw new TypeError('divide: both arguments must be valid numbers');
  }

  // Guard against division by zero
  if (b === 0) {
    throw new RangeError('divide: cannot divide by zero');
  }

  const result = a / b;

  // Guard against non-finite results (optional extra safety)
  if (!Number.isFinite(result)) {
    throw new Error('divide: result is not finite');
  }

  return result;
}

Usage:
try {
  console.log(divide(10, 2)); // 5
  console.log(divide(10, 0)); // throws
} catch (e) {
  console.error(e.name + ': ' + e.message);
}

If you prefer a non-throwing variant that returns an error object instead of throwing, tell me and I’ll adapt it.

